						<IMG src="http://www.archspace.org/image/forum/posticon.gif" border=0> posted 2005-03-08 18:43&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;
 						<A href="edit.php?board=sug&id=2116"><IMG alt="Edit/Delete Message" src="http://www.archspace.org/image/forum/edit.gif" border=0></A> 
			 			<A href="reply.php?board=sug&id=2116"><IMG alt="Reply w/Quote" src="http://www.archspace.org/image/forum/quote.gif" border=0></A> </FONT>
			  			<HR color=#000000 SIZE=-1>
			  			It seems that since the object of the game is to destroy the empire as fast as possible it encourages a race-like atmosphere which, to me, contradicts and takes focus from the interactive strategy aspect of the game that I and other gamers find so attractive.  The game becomes less interactive and dynamic since the main goal is more easily reached via cut-in-stone tactics and repetitive strategies.  Perhaps having an AI empire with Human allies would add to the challenge, as well as making the game more interactive, causing the implication of new strategies, and perhaps lengthening the gameplay (before the server is reset) each time (which would be quite appealing to less competitive players, who make up the majority of the Archspace population).  Another suggestion would be to recognize multiple &quot;winners&quot; for their various achievements.  Instead of just recognizing the most powerful, and those who defeated the empire the Archspace staff could recognize the largest financial empire, or perhaps &quot;best privateer&quot; (I'm not sure how feasable this is, but I've always enjoyed a good privateer :D).  What I've noticed most of all is that quite simply as new streamlined strategies develop, and players become more and more efficient at bringing down the empire the length of gameplay has shortened, and for many players all that means is that the fun is over until server reset, and then they start all over again.						<P align=right> </P>
					</TD>
				</TR>
	
		
